<review>Visited during Covid19 quarantine. One group at a time in the store.
Yo my goodness! The milky bun is ridiculous! Warm glazed donut with ice cream? Are you kidding me? SO GOOD! Get in here!
Their flavors are fun and yummy. They go way overboard with food dyes for eye appeal, though. Fudge Brownie ice cream is black, and will turn your mouth black. Monster Mint is also has a lot of food dye...very very green.<//review><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM7ElOBs5MwxgnBkgh5cTGKaC2dHCHmiWYnZ-ea=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNtBLapvTTzCSZybb32FRrxr0e1T5wy0CAsYGk8=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>< Resp>

< Text>
Oh man...Afters Ice Cream is great. I love donuts and ice cream so ice cream in a donut is heaven! I got a scoop of milk and cereal ice cream in a glazed milkybun topped with glazed flakes and roasted peanuts. The milkybun was nice and warm when I got it but it didn‚Äôt melt the ice cream. The flakes and peanuts added a crunch to it and the whole thing wasn‚Äôt too sweet. I definitely enjoyed it.< /Text>

< Text>
This place is VERY addictive! I love the staff at the new Highland Park location. They're very friendly, courteous, and employ quite a bit of common sense when it comes to customer service. They acknowledge everyone who comes in, and if they feel that it's taking too long with a customer they're serving, they make sure to pause and address the waiting customers by informing them that they'll be with them as soon as possible. I think that's fantastic!
Their biscotti cookie butter ice cream is To-Die-For! I love that I can add cereal as a topping on my ice cream. Diabetes is not on my "to get" agenda anytime soon, so I'm going to continue to stay away from the milky bun! But great spot!</Text>

< text>
There's lots to do at this park, but best to do them early in the day to avoid the things others have already mentioned.

The Frisbee golf course is quite awesome for those wanting a rougher feeling experience.

The kids play areas have a lot to offer, at the right times of day.

Not the best park to hold events or get-togethers though it could be easily if the city watched it a bit better.<//text>

< userid>
112620896413316064071< /userid>
<name>Kris Saradpon</name><time>1576535552170< /time>< rate>
2</rate>
< text>
I couldn't remember if I liked or disliked this place, but they one of the few spots opened early on Saturday morning and I figured it's hard to mess up Taco Shop food.
I ordered the bacon breakfast burrito and an horchata via drive thru.
The service was friendly and prompt.
This review is for the food. The tortilla was a thicker one and had burn spots, so there was too much bitterness and flour as I ate my burrito.  Also, the breakfast burrito had quartered red skinned potatoes that did not taste seasoned, but rather undercooked. So both the flavor and texture were disappointing.  The burrito overall needed salt because despite the saltiness from the bacon, it was not enough to compensate for the potato.  The scrambled eggs were cooked nicely.  I recommend using some tater tots in lieu of the red skin potatoes.
I also wish I had ordered sour cream to add some richness or moisture.
The shredded cheese was not melted despite the heat and that contributed to the lackluster.
The horchata was only cold on top where the ice was.  It got me thinking if I should be worried that the milk based horchata was like warm, but I assume it was made with a base.
I would be willing to give it another try in the future, but with another dish.< /text>

I didn't even get a chance to order! Let me explain... üëâ‚ÅâÔ∏èüí• Update: I tried to reach out to the Sombrero email in the reply to this review and I haven't heard back at all. They act like they care but they really don't it seems , that's unfortunate. üò±

It's early afternoon on a Sunday, a few people are in the dining room and a lot of people in the drive thru and the phone is also ringing.
There's 1 worker up in the front while I see at least 5 workers in the back.
The cooks in the back are placing orders on the counter and ringing their ready bell multiple times for the same order, while the guy in the front is taking orders from drive thru and answering the phone at the same time.

I stood there for 5 minutes watching the craziness.  Nobody had yet acknowledged that I was even there ready to order.

One of the dine-in customers was also standing next to me and it looked like he had been there for a while. When his order finally came out it was apparently wrong because the customer let the worker know it was supposed to be something else.

When the worker in the front told the guys in the back about the order more craziness started to occur when what seemed to be a shift leader wearing a headset came out and got involved in the conversation. The voice level then rose and the customer kept having to defend himself.  It was at this time I felt that it would take a serious amount of time for me to finally order and thensome if my order was wrong. Which I've had experience with many times.

Even though I had spent 10 minutes driving there (one way) I knew for sure I would be better off going to another taco shop close by.

By the looks of it the drive thru is their #1 priority and their customer service is piss poor.  After eating at their other locations the food quality is not worth the price nor the craziness.<//Text>

Years later, it seems the quality seems to have dipped, but i think it's the fault of the employees. Eutimio, the only person that's been there since the beginning, is the only one that gets it right consistently. 1576532885316<//Time>
< Rating>
4< /Rating>
<Text>Came here late at night a few times to swing by for a snack or the study. Overall, it was a pretty good experience except for a few things I will bring up in a general review of the establishment below.

Lantern Grill is located on 1st St, relatively close to Bristol and little bit further away from Santa Ana College. It is pretty easy to miss from traffic as it sits inside one of those small plazas on 1st. Parking is pretty small but this plaza does not get too busy so I would assume there would always be parking.

Going inside the first time, it can be a little bit overwhelming as there is alot going on. There is plenty of seating, although it is a little bit cramped. There is a no-shoe seating area next to the register that has more of a Japanese element to it as you are essentially seated in coffee tables with cushions the ground. It is a really nice and unique element. Other than the seating, there is a lot of decorations everywhere which can look a bit messy bit I see it as character. It can be a bit messy and dirty, but nothing too serious. The bathroom door doesn't have a lock, which scared me at first, but it cannot be opened from the outside so don't be too worried.

Both times that I have went, I tried their Boba Milk Tea which was pretty good but I would say is a bit pricey. The Boba Milk Tea with boba and a large upgrade ended up being $6 which was alot more than most boba places around that area. The food isn't too pricey as I got Popcorn Chicken for around $5 which is pretty typical.

Customer service was good and fast so there is nothing to complain about that.

Overall, I would definitely come back to study as they close at 2AM, which is definitely hard to find as most places close as late as 12AM. The food and drinks here are also great so that is a plus.<//Text>< pics>
None< /pics>

The food menu here is pretty simple for most of the entrees/dishes: pick a meat type. However, the food is pretty good. We got a "half" family tray and that was able to feed three grown men, so it's decent value. I'd recommend the pork here; the beef got a bit overcooked and felt more like beef jerky :( It's got more of a cafe feel, open late, and lots of drink options. It's also got a tatami-like area where you sit on the ground without shoes, if you like that.</Review>

< Text>
I would give them a zero if I could. I've been to the location a couple of times and I like their smooothies. When I went there I bought a smoothie and was given no receipt. My friend ordered a smothie right after me and they were given a receipt and told "fill out this online survey for a free smoothie(or drink don't quite remember)". I after that I asked for my receipt but my receipt didn't have anything about a survey. I decided to go to the same location again. Once again I wasn't given a receipt but with my super awesome vision I was able to see the original receipt. It had the survey thingy buuuuut the cashier didn't give it to me when I was about to reach over to receive it. Instead she placed in a fat stack of other original receipts. When I asked her for the receipt she instead printed a second one out, the one the doesn't have the good deal. So I thought maybe it was just a one time thing. So later my friend wanted to get some juice so we returned but she made the mistake if asking the receipt before it was printed out. In this case they must have hit no receipt then printed out the second receipt. This is how you are robbed of a free smoothie or juice. I don't blame them for doing this though because their juices and smoothies run 8 dollars for larges but I'm sure they would only give you a small anyway but that's still five dollars. Usually this stupid stuff doesn't matter to me and I never fill out the surveys anyway but I was irked that they would take the chance to even fill it out. Anyway I how you guys will notice it next time you visit the jamba Juice location at coddington mall.</Text>

<response>None< /response><Name>Cathleen ItalianoSimonson<//Name><Review>Staff was friendly and helpful from first call. My visit  was a referral.

I had had an MRI of my knee and it showed a meniscus tear and other issues. (Bone to bone, arthritis.  I was seen on time.   Dr Arianjam allowed me to record my appointment with him because I could not have someone with me because of Covid. So I could share it with my family.  I want to avoid surgery,  unless last resort.  I am a Chef,  Event planner and coordinator and need to be on my feet, using my legs.  I am 65 years old, in good physical shape.  No weight issues and I Peloton almost daily.  I take zero meds.

Afterca lengthily discussion, I decided to go with the cortisone injection to relieve the inflammation and swelling for now.  He suggested a new in office procedure called mi-eye which is a camera that looks inside the injured area.  Easy procedure.  He numbed then area and inserted a long needle in my knee.  No pain and attached it all to an iPad type screen so I could watch.  He was so personable through the procedure answering all  of my questions.  The bad news was I have meniscus "shredding".  Which cannot be repaired in an orthroscopic  clean up.  During the procedure he injected the cortisone since the needle was already in the knee.  A bit of gauze and tape and I was ready to leave. Barely and bleeding.  The staff at front desk told me they are the only group in my area that has this technology.  Today I woke up pain free!  Swelling almost gone.

I would highly recommend him and his practice.  After two failed disc surgeries years ago with a physician in Fullerton, I am most definitely apprehensive of surgeries.   He read that immediately because he took the time and "listened" to my concerns and understood.  A trait many doctors are lacking.  You always feel rushed.  However, not with him.

Never for a moment did I feel that I was just another patient with him or with anyone working in this practice.   I would highly recommend Premier!.  I wish I could give them 10 stars .</Review><user>103055759963579838964< /user>< gmap_id>

<Review>Our old car had the water pump blow out while driving. We limped the vehicle to a parking lot and had it towed to Vacaville Toyota. Vacaville refused to accept the trade in after we offered up the Texas title it had. Lucas from the Jimmy Vasser sales department called and told me that he would be more than happy to sell me a vehicle the next day if I wanted. He offered me more on my trade in. Offered to tow the vehicle from Vacaville. As well as offering me very nearly the same price Vacaville did. For a car with added packages the one in Vacaville did not have. He also sent someone to pick us up as we did not have a vehicle to drive at all that day. We were picked up when we asked to be. The driver was friendly and even made a stop so the misuses and I could grab Starbucks. We were paired with Kyle from sales when we arrived. He had the car detailed and fully gassed up sitting in front of sales when we arrived. We test drove the vehicle as Kyle adeptly explained the features and answered all the questions we had. Upon returning to the dealership Kyle and I sat down and quickly filled out some paperwork. He walked us over to finance where we ran into an issue. Our down payment was coming from a card that was being declined (we assume a stoppage due to the fact it was a large "abnormal" charge). The sales team let us take our new vehicle home so I could grab my check book so we could complete the deal that day. All things considered I am not sure how the day could have gone better. The level of customer service we received was in the top two ever (neck and neck with USAA). The process from picking us up at home to driving our new vehicle off the lot was near seamless. The one issue we did have was our fault and the sales team quickly offered a painless remedy. I even managed to discover Kyle had a shared passion for UFC and got to chat about sports while buying a new car. (2020 Hybrid Rav-4 LE) P.S. By far the worst car buying experience in 30 years! My wife and I went into the dealership to purchase a car for our daughter. The salesmen were friendly. We agreed on a price. First we were told the car could be ready in 2-3 hours. Then, it was that evening. Then, the next day. When we tried to reach them the next day for update information, the car was a different color. We still agreed and were told that the car would be ready to go on Monday at 4:30. We told him that we were not signing anything until we saw the car. At that point we pressed him and he admitted that the car was not even there yet. Anthony Beaver set me up for an oil change and quotes on further service mostmrecently, as well as proactively offering me the software update I had forgotten to make an appointment for while my car was already there. I had to fight the Santa Rosa dealer to honor any warranty work previously and was pleasantly surprised by the offer. I expected a laundry list of recommended service after the included inspection. They didn't try to upsell me a single service and he answered all my questions about the inspection and needed maintenance with a smile. I'll be back for regular service at this location thanks to thier great customer service, honesty and treating me like a valued customer even though I'm not in the market for a new car.< /Text>

<Review>I gave them one star because there is no choice for no star at all. Please be careful with this dealership, they will lie to you and rip you off. I bought a new car 6 year ago with a $2500 six years extended warranty, and was told I will get my money back if I did not use this warranty in six years. The sales manager never told me that this is a third party company, not Toyota itself. Now, six years later, when I went to them and claimed my reimbursement, they told me that this third party company called NADS went to bankrupt several years ago and I won't get my money back. All these years, this dealership never noticed me about this situation.  The manager was so rude that I can't even finish the conversation. 6 years ago, he was very nice and convinced me to buy that warranty, and I trusted him. I heard that Honda dealer used the same 3rd party company, but they are offering their customers with purchasing credits or service credits to make it up. <Rate>5</Rate><Review>I bought a new car from Jimmy Vasser Toyota.  They all treated me well, and the dealership is worth five stars.  However, I am writing to commend two particular individuals at the dealership:  salesman Ron Cooper and sales assistant Victoria Young-Cooper. Again, everybody I dealt with was good; but, Ron and Victoria are truly exceptional.   If you want to ensure that you get a five-star experience when shopping here, you should insist on dealing with Ron for sales and Victoria for the invaluable extra-credit service she provides.
Ron is fair and honest. The price I paid was quite good, although I don't know whether Ron has total control over that.  He was, however, someone whom I felt that I could trust; and, he was highly recommended to me by someone whom I am quite certain I can trust: Jon Sciacqua at Toyota Walnut Creek. More on Jon and Toyota Walnut Creek, after I have finished celebrating the glory of Ron and Victoria.
Ron and Victoria are wonderful people. They will give you wonderful treatment as a customer; and, they will give you wonderful treatment as a human being.  They are kind and honest and caring.  They really took great care of me.
I was something unusual for a car dealership:  I hadn't bought a new car since July 1988. Really.  I was...and still am...driving my beloved 1988 Nissan Sentra four-speed stick no-radio sedan.  I tried to learn about purchasing a modern car, did a lot of studying prior to contacting dealers; still, I was a challenge for the sales people. Ron & Victoria rose to the challenge.
Ron was very patient. He taught me a lot that I hadn't known.    He let me do what I wanted on the test drive. He answered all my questions.    He made the sale [with the significant assistant of Manny in the service department, who waxed and polished the car sufficiently to make up for the damage wrought by 220 days out on the lot].
Then came the paperwork, which was something like going through chemo; but, it always is, and Jill and Jim were as good as anybody could be in presenting a blizzard of dense legal documentation.
But then came Victoria.  By this time, it was 8:00 pm.  She stayed on, without the faintest hint of complaint, and devoted over two hours to teaching me how to drive this car.  She synced my phone to the car's Bluetooth, she found and programmed my favorite radio stations...this for a guy whose car of 30 years had no radio at all...and she taught me how to drive this car.    She was still with me after 10:00 pm.  So was Ron, who was Victoria's ride home (and Victoria's husband).  After all that, they were concerned about me. It was dark, and I had to drive through confusing roads...Napa is not that easy to find...in order to reach I-80.   Ron rode with me, and Victoria led us all the way to the on ramp to 80.    Once on 80, I was fine...but they were still concerned.  Victoria texted me to confirm that I had arrived safely home.
Buy a Toyota, buy it from Ron and Victoria at Jimmy Vasser in Napa.   I don't think you could do better.   Except, maybe...
A footnote:  Before I went up to Napa, I had been dealing with Jon Sciacqua...an Italian name, pronounced "shock-wa"...at Toyota Walnut Creek.   I dealt with several people there. All were very good. Jon is absolutely great. He is totally honest; and, isn't that what car shoppers are most concerned about, in dealing with dealerships?   My car was new, but Jon primarily sells used cars.  He is the absolute antithesis of the dark stereotype of a used-car salesman.  If you want to get competitive bids, I suggest Napa Toyota, as well as Walnut Creek.
Wanna know how honest Jon is?   He had to offer a fixed price.   New owners, new policy.  Some evil algorithm chose an awful price for my car, a Yaris iA (which is actually a rebadged Mazda2).  Jon couldn't do anything about it.  He recommended Ron at Napa. I saved $800 at Napa.    I owe that to Jon.
Five stars for both dealerships; five thousand stars for Victoria & Ron & Jon.
If you've read this far, you've earned a silver star and a box of Godiva chocolates.< /Review><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< response>

< review>
After looking at various Toyota 4Runners for over a month and visiting multiple dealerships, I ended up at Jimmy Vasser Toyota to check out a used one I had found online.  I initially spoke with Kyle on the phone, but ended up working with Tai when I arrived. Tai was great, very knowledgable and not pushy at all.  He let me test drive the car in various conditions, as I requested, and showed me the off-roading features I was interested in. He also let me take the car off the lot to a local mechanic so I could get another opinion since it is a used vehicle.

As these things go, the whole process was relatively painless. I ended up purchasing the vehicle. I also had to leave my car on the lot for over a week because of my schedule (had to fly east for two funerals), and they kindly let me park it there.

Overall I would recommend the dealership‚Äî and Tai, Kyle and Will were all great help. After I purchased the car, Will spent time explaining the off-road features to me, which was very helpful.</review>
